ion ciphers, connections between ciphers and computer encryption, stream ciphers, public-key ciphers, and ciphers involving exponentiation. He concludes by looking at the future of ciphers and where cryptography might be headed. The Mathematics of Secrets reveals the mathematics working stealthily in the science of coded messages.A blog describing new developments and historical discoveries in cryptography related to the material in this book is accessible at http://press.princeton.edu/titles/10826.html.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCiphers. 0aComputer security. 0aCryptographyxMathematics. 7aCOMPUTERS / Security / Cryptography.2bisacsh  aAdaptive chosen-ciphertext attack.  aAdvanced Encryption Standard.  aAffine cipher.  aAlice and Bob.  aAutokey cipher.  aBlock cipher mode of operation.  aBlock cipher.  aBlock size (cryptography).  aBrute-force attack.  aBrute-force search.  aCaesar cipher.  aCalculation.  aChosen-ciphertext attack.  aChosen-plaintext attack.  aCipher.  aCiphertext-only attack.  aCiphertext.  aCodebook.  aCommunication Theory of Secrecy Systems.  aComputational problem.  aConfusion and diffusion.  aCorrelation attack.  aCraig Gentry (computer scientist).  aCryptanalysis.  aCryptogram.  aCryptographic engineering.  aCryptographic hash function.  aCryptography Research.  aCryptography.  aCryptosystem.  aData Encryption Standard.  aDifferential cryptanalysis.  aDiffie–Hellman key exchange.  aDiscrete logarithm.  aDisquisitiones Arithmeticae.  aDual EC DRBG.  aElGamal encryption.  aElliptic curve cryptography.  aEncryption.  aEnigma machine.  aEuler's theorem.  aFast Software Encryption.  aFeistel cipher.  aFermat's little theorem.  aForward secrecy.  aGrover's algorithm.  aHill cipher.  aHomomorphic 